Title:
sign-expired — Signtool modification for expired certificates

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This repository provides a modified workflow to allow Microsoft’s `signtool.exe` to sign binaries using expired code-signing certificates. It does this by DLL hijacking: a custom-built `XmlLite.dll` is placed next to the official, Microsoft-signed `signtool.exe` so it is loaded at runtime. The injected DLL alters/patches behavior so the same signing command works even when the certificate is expired. The repo includes the C++ source (`dllmain.cpp`) and bundled binaries (`signtool.exe`, `XmlLite.dll`). It is primarily useful for red teamers, malware developers, and researchers exploring Authenticode trust edge-cases and signing tool abuse. It’s interesting because it leverages a trusted Microsoft-signed utility plus side-loading to bypass expected certificate validity enforcement.

Technical Focus:
- DLL search order hijacking / DLL side-loading (XmlLite.dll)
- Authenticode code signing and certificate validity checks
- Runtime patching/hooking inside `signtool.exe`
- Windows trust chain / signing tool behavior
- C++ DLL entrypoint manipulation (`DllMain`)

Use Cases:
- Testing how security products validate Authenticode signatures vs certificate expiration
- Simulating attacker tradecraft that abuses trusted signed tooling (LOLBIN-adjacent)
- Researching Windows signing pipeline and trust enforcement gaps
- Building detections for DLL side-loading against developer tooling (e.g., signtool)

Keywords:
signtool, Authenticode, code signing, expired certificate, DLL hijacking, DLL side-loading, XmlLite.dll, Windows, trust validation, certificate chain, signature verification, WinVerifyTrust, DllMain, C++, Microsoft-signed binary, LOLBIN, supply chain, EDR evasion